{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's Urdu poetry collection *Bang-e-Dara*, 'huzuri' (appearing in transliteration primarily as *huzoor*) evokes a state of intimate spiritual proximity or \"being-present-with\" exalted figures—most prominently the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him)—or symbolically the divine light. It connotes devotional surrender, repose amid worldly turmoil, and mystical encounter, often framed as a visionary or prayerful submission.[^1]\n\nThe term is central to the poem \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" (\"In the Exalted Prophet's Presence\"), where the poet-nightingale is transported by angels to the Prophet's radiant court:  \n> The angels led me to the Prophet's court so bright,  \n> And brought me to the presence of Mercy's guiding Light.[^2]  \n\nThere, it addresses the Prophet as \"O Presence!\" (*Huzoor!*), lamenting earthly transience while offering martyrs' blood as a gift in that sacred nearness.[^3]\n\nSymbolically, in \"Shama-o-Parwana\" (\"The Candle and the Moth\"), the moth's annihilation *tere huzoor mein* (\"in your presence,\" i.e., before the candle as divine symbol) becomes its ecstatic prayer:  \n> To fall before you is its sacred prayer and rite;  \n> Its tiny heart finds bliss in burning with delight.[^4]\n\nNo explicit philosophical definition of *huzuri* appears in the available Iqbal corpus (limited to *Bang-e-Dara*); its meaning emerges poetically as Sufi-inflected devotion and self-loss in divine companionship. Other instances (e.g., in Ghalib's *Diwan*) use it more courtly, but Iqbal elevates it to prophetic intimacy.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 11 \"Huzoor Risalat Ma'ab Mein\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/#p-50452a)).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 11 ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/#p-c8ea02)).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 11 ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/11-huzoor-risalat-maab-mein/translation/#p-14a317)).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 41 \"Shama-o-Parwana\" ([paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/41-shama-o-parwana/translation/#p-d2c29e)).",
